According to an alarming new study released Monday by the University of Chicago, children raised in households where alcoholism is present are at a significantly greater risk of writing and performing a one-man show than those who grow up in a more stable environment.The study found that males raised by alcoholic parents are 40 percent more likely to someday force their friends to attend a self-penned theatrical production about their life experiences, and the same painful behavior is eight times more prevalent in women over the age of 30 who have alcoholic fathers than those who do not.According to the report, of the 250 one-man shows that premiered last month, three quarters of them, including , , and , were directly linked to a relative who abused alcohol.“Before you know it, they’re caught in the self- destructive pattern of doing the show every other Friday.